{% set simpleCode %}<blockquote>
  The best way to predict the future is to invent it.
</blockquote>{% endset %}

{% set footerCode %}<blockquote>
  The best way to predict the future is to invent it.
  <footer>Alan Kay</footer>
</blockquote>{% endset %}

{% set fullCode %}<blockquote cite="https://example.com/source">
  Any sufficiently advanced technology is indistinguishable from magic.
  <footer>Arthur C. Clarke, <cite>Profiles of the Future</cite></footer>
</blockquote>{% endset %}

{% set figureCode %}<figure class="quote">
  <blockquote>
    Good design is as little design as possible.
  </blockquote>
  <figcaption>Dieter Rams, <cite>Less and More</cite></figcaption>
</figure>{% endset %}

{% set academicCode %}<blockquote cite="https://doi.org/10.1000/example">
  <p>The results demonstrate a statistically significant correlation
  between design simplicity and user satisfaction scores (p &lt; 0.01).</p>
  <footer>Smith &amp; Jones (2025), <cite>Journal of Web Usability</cite>,
  Vol. 12, pp. 45&ndash;62</footer>
</blockquote>{% endset %}

{% set langCode %}<blockquote lang="fr">
  Je pense, donc je suis.
  <footer>René Descartes</footer>
</blockquote>{% endset %}

{% set blockquoteCssCode %}blockquote {
  padding-inline-start: var(--size-m);
  border-inline-start: var(--border-width-thick) solid var(--color-border);
  color: var(--color-text-muted);
  font-style: italic;
}

/* Attribution — auto em-dash prefix */
blockquote footer,
blockquote cite {
  display: block;
  margin-block-start: var(--size-s);
  font-style: normal;
  font-size: var(--font-size-sm);

  &::before {
    content: "— ";
  }
}{% endset %}

{% set proseCode %}/* Hanging punctuation for typographic refinement (Safari) */
blockquote { hanging-punctuation: first last; }

/* Italic de-emphasis inside blockquotes */
:where(blockquote) :where(i, em) {
  font-style: normal;
  font-weight: var(--font-weight-medium);
}{% endset %}

<section>
    <h2>Description</h2>
    <p>The <code>&lt;blockquote&gt;</code> element represents an extended quotation from another source. VB styles it with a left border, muted italic text, and automatic em-dash attribution via <code>&lt;footer&gt;</code> or <code>&lt;cite&gt;</code> inside the blockquote.</p>
    <p>VB also adds typographic refinements: <code>hanging-punctuation: first last</code> for Safari, and a de-emphasis reset for <a href="/docs/elements/native/em/"><code>&lt;em&gt;</code></a>/<a href="/docs/elements/native/i/"><code>&lt;i&gt;</code></a> inside blockquotes (since the blockquote is already visually offset, double-italic would be redundant).</p>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>When to Use</h2>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Extended quotations:</strong> Quotes from books, articles, speeches</li>
      <li><strong>Testimonials:</strong> Customer quotes and endorsements</li>
      <li><strong>Pull quotes:</strong> Highlighted excerpts (use <code>&lt;figure class="quote"&gt;</code>)</li>
      <li><strong>Academic citations:</strong> Referenced passages with source attribution</li>
      <li><strong>Epigraphs:</strong> Opening quotes in articles or chapters</li>
    </ul>
    <h3>When NOT to Use</h3>
    <ul>
      <li>For short inline quotes &mdash; use <a href="/docs/elements/native/q/"><code>&lt;q&gt;</code></a></li>
      <li>For content that isn't a quotation (even if you want the visual style)</li>
      <li>For indenting content &mdash; use CSS margins or <a href="/docs/elements/custom-elements/layout-stack/"><code>&lt;layout-stack&gt;</code></a></li>
    </ul>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>Examples</h2>

    <browser-window src="/docs/snippets/demos/blockquote-examples.html" url="blockquote-examples.html" title="Blockquote patterns" shadow></browser-window>

    <code-block language="html" show-lines label="Simple blockquote">{{ simpleCode | escape }}</code-block>
    <code-block language="html" show-lines label="Footer attribution">{{ footerCode | escape }}</code-block>
    <code-block language="html" show-lines label="Full attribution with cite">{{ fullCode | escape }}</code-block>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>Attribution Patterns</h2>
    <p>VB auto-prepends an em dash (&mdash;) to <code>&lt;footer&gt;</code> or <code>&lt;cite&gt;</code> elements inside a blockquote. Combine both for author + work title:</p>

    <table class="props-table">
      <thead>
        <tr><th>Pattern</th><th>Use Case</th></tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr>
          <td><code>&lt;footer&gt;Author Name&lt;/footer&gt;</code></td>
          <td>Simple attribution (person)</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td><code>&lt;cite&gt;Work Title&lt;/cite&gt;</code></td>
          <td>Work title only</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td><code>&lt;footer&gt;Author, &lt;cite&gt;Work&lt;/cite&gt;&lt;/footer&gt;</code></td>
          <td>Author + work (recommended)</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td><code>cite="URL"</code> attribute</td>
          <td>Machine-readable source URL (not displayed)</td>
        </tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>Pull Quote (figure pattern)</h2>
    <p>Wrap a blockquote in <code>&lt;figure class="quote"&gt;</code> with a <code>&lt;figcaption&gt;</code> for pull quote styling. The figure removes blockquote margins and adds its own em-dash to the caption:</p>

    <code-block language="html" show-lines label="Pull quote figure">{{ figureCode | escape }}</code-block>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>Academic Citations</h2>
    <p>For academic and research writing, use the <code>cite</code> attribute with a DOI or URL for machine-readable provenance. The footer can include full bibliographic information:</p>

    <browser-window src="/docs/snippets/demos/blockquote-academic.html" url="blockquote-academic.html" title="Academic citations" shadow></browser-window>

    <code-block language="html" show-lines label="Academic citation">{{ academicCode | escape }}</code-block>

    <p>The <code>cite</code> attribute is not displayed but is available to scripts, search engines, and citation tools. Future VB features may auto-generate bibliography sections from <code>cite</code> attributes.</p>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>Foreign Language Quotes</h2>
    <p>Use the <code>lang</code> attribute when quoting in another language. VB's <a href="/docs/i18n/">i18n system</a> will apply appropriate font family and line height:</p>

    <code-block language="html" show-lines label="Foreign language quote">{{ langCode | escape }}</code-block>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>CSS Reference</h2>
    <code-block language="css" show-lines label="Blockquote CSS">{{ blockquoteCssCode | escape }}</code-block>

    <h3>Prose Refinements</h3>
    <code-block language="css" show-lines label="Typographic refinements">{{ proseCode | escape }}</code-block>

    <table class="props-table">
      <thead>
        <tr><th>Feature</th><th>Implementation</th></tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr>
          <td>Left border</td>
          <td><code>border-inline-start</code> (RTL-safe)</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>Em-dash attribution</td>
          <td><code>::before { content: "— " }</code> on footer/cite</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>Hanging punctuation</td>
          <td><code>hanging-punctuation: first last</code> (progressive, Safari)</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>Italic de-emphasis</td>
          <td><code>em</code>/<code>i</code> inside blockquote reset to normal + medium weight</td>
        </tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>Accessibility</h2>
    <ul>
      <li>Screen readers may announce "blockquote" before reading content</li>
      <li>Users can navigate between blockquotes on a page</li>
      <li>The <code>cite</code> attribute is not announced but is available programmatically</li>
      <li>Always provide attribution for external quotations</li>
      <li>Use <code>lang</code> for quotes in different languages so screen readers switch pronunciation</li>
    </ul>
  </section>

